data.value: Venus stands on a large seashell in the painting, which has become one of the most recognizable symbols in art history. The shell is not just a backdrop to the goddess’s dramatic entrance; it is imbued with symbolic meaning. In ancient times, the shell was often linked to fertility, beauty, and the sea, making it the perfect vehicle for Venus’s birth. The shell, in fact, references the idea of rebirth and new beginnings, which aligns with Venus’s role in mythology as the goddess who governs love and creation.
